tner became Vermont's attorney general and a federal judge.","number":2},{"category":"character","header":"He waited eighty-seven years for the Red Sox","body":"Born eleven months before the 1918 title, he followed the team through generations of broadcasters before they won again just after his birthday in 2004. He chased a golf ball with the same patience into his nineties.","number":3}],"sources":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus"},{"institution_id":"INST165","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Robert Tileston","last_name":"Gannett","display_name":"Robert Tileston Gannett","gender":"male","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Vermont legislator and Brattleboro lawyer","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781015747/134146701_299b2877-38e1-4d78-9245-6b6ed1d459fa_thto13.jpg"},"military_service":[{"war":"World War II","branch":"United States Army","rank":"Major","notes":"Field artillery, combat service in Europe 1944-1945."}],"career":[{"role":"Attorney","organization":"Brattleboro, Vermont"},{"role":"Member","organization":"Vermont House of Representatives","start_year":1953,"end_year":1961},{"role":"Member","organization":"Vermont State Senate","start_year":1972,"end_year":1993}],"birth":{"year":1917,"country":"United States","month":9,"day":26},"death":{"year":2012,"country":"United States","month":8,"day":26,"city":"Brattleboro","state":"Vermont"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM781"},"education":[{"school_name":"Milton Academy","dates":"1935"},{"institution_id":"INST002","dates":"1939","type":"graduation","notes":"A.B."},{"institution_id":"INST165","dates":"1942","type":"graduation","notes":"LL.B."}],"slug":"robert-tileston-gannett-1917"},"HD6122":{"id":"HD6122","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"generation_from_thomas":11},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"I1667","mother_id":"HD6088"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I1668","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1,"marriage_year":1948}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"Named for the uncle lost over France","body":"Quentin Roosevelt, the president's youngest son, was shot down over France in 1918. Five years later this niece was born and given his name to keep — Judith Quentin Derby.","number":1},{"category":"family","header":"She married into a dynasty of scientists","body":"Her husband and his father both made their names studying the brain and the eye, a rare scientific lineage. She died in 1973, in her forties, the mother of three.","number":2}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X3160","display_label":"was her father-in-law, who built the Ames room illusion"},{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X3161","display_label":"was her mother-in-law, wife of the Ames-room scientist"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Judith Quentin","last_name":"Ames","display_name":"Judith Quentin Derby Ames","gender":"female","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"TR's granddaughter; wife of neuroscientist Del Ames","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781015830/medium_ikk3xc.jpg"},"military_service":[],"career":[],"birth":{"year":1923,"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1973,"country":"United States","month":9,"day":26,"city":"Boston","state":"Massachusetts"},"burial":{},"education":[],"slug":"judith-quentin-ames-1923"},"I1668":{"id":"I1668","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["science"],"notable_blurb":"Harvard neuroscientist; created the Ames medium","primary_url":"https://fa.hms.harvard.edu/sites/g/files/omnuum4521/files/hmsofa/files/memorialminute_adelbert_ames.pdf","primary_url_label":"Harvard Medical School memorial minute"},"parents":{"father_id":"X3160","mother_id":"X3161"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6122","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1,"marriage_year":1948}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"science","header":"The fluid that keeps brain tissue alive","body":"He devised an artificial cerebrospinal fluid, the Ames medium, that lets scientists keep nervous-system tissue working for days outside the body. It remains the standard solution for the purpose today.","number":1},{"category":"science","header":"The no-reflow phenomenon","body":"Working with rabbit brains, he showed that after enough minutes without blood the smallest vessels clamp shut and will not refill, the first irreversible injury of a stroke. The finding later proved true in the heart and other organs.","number":2},{"category":"character","header":"Skiing competitively into his late eighties","body":"Class valedictorian at Exeter and Phi Beta Kappa at Harvard, he kept racing in masters ski events until almost ninety. He was last seen on cross-country skis at ninety-six.","number":3}],"sources":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST103","relationship":"alumnus"},{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus"},{"institution_id":"INST171","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"H04422","display_label":"pioneered cardiac defibrillation as a Hook